CDs were synthesized through a simple one-pot hydrothermal method at 160 °C, 12 h as shown in Scheme 1. The UV–Vis and fluorescence spectra were examined to evaluated the optical properties of the as-prepared CDs. As seen in Fig. 1
                        A, when excitated at λex = 360 nm, the maximum emission intensity (460 nm) of the colloidal aqueous solution of the CDs reached (insert: a bright blue emission). The optimum excitation band with 360 nm of CDs matched nearly with the UV–Vis absorption peak. The fluorescence of the CDs comes from the broad absorption band in the UV region of the CDs [46]. In the UV–Vis absorption spectrum of the CDs (Fig. 1A), there was an obvious absorption shoulder at around 250 nm. At 355 nm, there was a clear absorption peak and it extended from the ultraviolet absorption region to the visible light absorption region. According to the literature [47], the absorption peak at 250 nm was referred to the π-π* transition of the CC bond in the aromatic sp2 domain. The peak around 355 nm was assigned to the n-π* transition of the CO bond. Furthermore, similar to most reported CDs [18,40,46], CDs exhibited typical excitation-dependent photoluminescence (PL) behavior (Fig. S1). The optimal emission wavelength of the as-prepared CDs changed from 457 to 482 nm as the excitation wavelength varied from 300 to 430 nm. 460 nm was the maximum emission intensity of the as-prepared CDs at the excitation wavelength of 360 nm. The fluorescence lifetime of the synthesized CDs in aqueous solution at 25 °C is 4.96 ns, and the absolute QY is 9.25 % (Table 1
                        ).
